gan, Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Irland","Ireland, United Kingdom":"Ireland, Orkney, Skotland, United Kingdom","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Irland","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irland","Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irland"},"nl":{"From 1339 to 1343–":"van 1339 to 1343–Overleden","1339–1388":"1339–1388","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Overleden","1339–Female":"1339–Overleden","From 1339 to 1343":"van 1339 to 1343","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"circa 1372","1339":"1339","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ierland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Ierland","Ireland, United Kingdom":"Ireland, Orkney, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Ierland","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ierland","Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ierland"},"en":{"From 1339 to 1343–":"from 1339 to 1343–Deceased","1339–1388":"1339–1388","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Deceased","1339–Female":"1339–Deceased","From 1339 to 1343":"from 1339 to 1343","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"about 1372","1339":"1339","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Ireland","Ireland, United Kingdom":"Ireland, Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland","Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Plunkett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a metathesized form of Plouquenet in Ille-et-Villaine, Brittany, so named from Breton <i>plou</i> ‘parish’ (from Latin <i>plebs</i> ‘people’) + <i>Guenec</i>, the personal name (a diminutive of <i>guen</i> ‘white’) of a somewhat obscure saint. As an Irish name, it has been Gaelicized as <b>Pluincéid</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Plunket","meanings":["English (northern) and Irish: variant of   Plunkett  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Plunkett was born from 1339 to 1343, in Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland. She married Sir Richard Plunket in 1369, in Diocese of Meath, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in her hometown, and was buried in Ireland, Orkney, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"From 1339 to 1343–":"1339 kuni 1343–Surnud","1339–1388":"1339–1388","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","1339–Female":"1339–Surnud","From 1339 to 1343":"1339 kuni 1343","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"umbes 1372","1339":"1339","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Iirimaa","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Iirimaa","Ireland, United Kingdom":"Ireland, Orkney, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Iirimaa","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Iirimaa","Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"From 1339 to 1343–":"vuodesta 1339 vuoteen 1343–Kuollut","1339–1388":"1339–1388","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Kuollut","1339–Female":"13